    },
    {
      "id": "ba2adf154a84fbd59d697ed59ce1aec76090adb3",
      "author": {
        "_account_id": 2,
        "name": "Jenkins",
        "username": "hudson",
        "inactive": true
      },
      "date": "2012-08-25 10:01:57.000000000",
      "message": "Patch Set 1: Verified\n\nBuild Successful \n \nhttp://build.whamcloud.com/job/lustre-reviews/8626/ : SUCCESS",
      "accounts_in_message": [],
      "_revision_number": 1
    },
    {
      "id": "094585746f25db2bf2139e706b4751c759b8d143",
      "author": {
        "_account_id": 117,
        "name": "Andreas Dilger",
        "email": "adilger@thelustrecollective.com",
        "username": "adilger"
      },
      "date": "2012-08-25 17:11:07.000000000",
      "message": "Patch Set 1: I would prefer that you didn't submit this\n\nThis isn't do simple as just changing the bit value. This flag is used by userspace applications and in the Lustre network protocol, and is not tied to a specific Lustre version.\n\nI don't think FMODE_NONOTIFY is exposed to userspace, so some mechanism needs to be in place to use a different value for \"FMODE_LOV_DELAY_CREATE\" inside the client kernel, and then convert the flag for Lustre to keep the same value for MDS_LOV_DELAY_CREATE over the network.\n\nWithin llapi_open_file_stripe() it would be possible to mknod() the file first, then setxattr() on the file before opening it, but that is going to add multiple RPCs to the open process. Alternately, I thought there was another O_ flag added recently which is like \"local only\" to allow ioctls and such on block device files that do not exist. I can't recall the name right now. \n\nSince this is a significant issue affecting many different Lustre releases, it should be tracked in its own Jira ticket.",
      "accounts_in_message": [],
      "_revision_number": 1
    },
    {
      "id": "9177a8278daddc685516131dd4dd07ea701a3dfb",
      "author": {
        "_account_id": 242,
        "name": "Liu Xuezhao",
        "email": "xuezhao.liu@emc.com",
        "username": "XuezhaoLiu",
        "inactive": true
      },
      "date": "2012-08-26 03:06:30.000000000",
      "message": "Patch Set 1:\n\nHi Andreas,\n\nChanging O_LOV_DELAY_CREATE does not affect network protocol between client and server. Because the below logic:\n\n        if (flags & O_LOV_DELAY_CREATE)\n                cr_flags |= MDS_OPEN_DELAY_CREATE;\n\ninside mdc_open_pack -> mds_pack_open_flags() already translates client's O_LOV_DELAY_CREATE to server's MDS_OPEN_DELAY_CREATE.\nSo this change will not bring compatible issues between different version's client and server.\n\nO_LOV_DELAY_CREATE's only usage is pass in a special flag for setstripe a new file. If opened with O_LOV_DELAY_CREATE, then lustre doesn't do the object creation or open until ll_lov_setstripe() ioctl is called. \n\nuser space's llapi_file_open_pool and llite's ll_file_open/ll_lov_setstripe_ea_info already have all needed logic to handle it.\n\nBut for kernel after 2.6.36, O_LOV_DELAY_CREATE conflicts with FMODE_NONOTIFY and will be cleared in vfs' do_sys_open -> build_open_flags(). So I change the definition to an un-used bit since it does not affect on-the-wire protocol.\n\nFor the \"another O_ flag\" you mentioned, I think it is O_PATH added by kernel commit 1abf0c718f15a56a0a435588d1b104c7a37dc9bd . It will create the inode but assign an empty_fops (f->f_op = &empty_fops;) which breaks hooking with ll_file_operations, I think O_PATH cannot be used in this case.\n\nThanks.",
      "accounts_in_message": [],
      "_revision_number": 1
    },
    {
      "id": "b6e67571ba45023d26bd98d5f96452b6aee0af2a",
      "author": {
        "_account_id": 147,
        "name": "Maloo",
        "email": "maloo@whamcloud.com",
        "username": "maloo",
        "tags": [
          "SERVICE_USER"
        ]
      },
      "date": "2012-08-26 03:17:32.000000000",
      "message": "Patch Set 1: Fails\n\nTests received by maloo, run on CentOS release 6.3/x86_64: (https://maloo.whamcloud.com/test_sessions/4f548340-ef2a-11e1-9426-52540035b04c).  Ran 14 tests.  1 tests failed: sanity.",
      "accounts_in_message": [],
      "_revision_number": 1
    },
    {
      "id": "2b4065c4e9fbfdbc90ac60f1755125cf6e09220e",
      "author": {
        "_account_id": 136,
        "name": "Alexey Lyashkov",
        "email": "alexey.lyashkov@hpe.com",
        "username": "shadow"
      },
      "date": "2012-08-29 15:32:43.000000000",
      "message": "Patch Set 1:\n\nAndreas, \n\nyou are wrong. That flag isn't used in lustre network protocol for long time (as i remember after 1.6.5 or 1.8.0) so main question about using older userland application with a new modules, but that is easy to resolve via package builds. just add a dependence line (conflict with tools version less ... ).",
      "accounts_in_message": [],
      "_revision_number": 1
    },
    {
      "id": "bfdd2b2cd506dcdc01b5c0184f0454b299186e4b",
      "author": {
        "_account_id": 190,
        "name": "Iurii Golovach",
        "email": "Iurii_Golovach@xyratex.com",
        "username": "Iurii",
        "inactive": true
      },
      "date": "2012-08-29 15:39:10.000000000",
      "message": "Patch Set 1: I would prefer that you didn't submit this\n\nHi Lui,\n\nto pass sanity.sh test you have to add next code to your patch:\n\n\ndiff --git a/lustre/tests/sanity.sh b/lustre/tests/sanity.sh\nindex 88ab9aa..90055e2 100644\n--- a/lustre/tests/sanity.sh\n+++ b/lustre/tests/sanity.sh\n@@ -1624,7 +1624,7 @@ test_33b() {\n         rm -fr $DIR/d33\n         mkdir -p $DIR/d33\n         chown $RUNAS_ID $DIR/d33\n-        $RUNAS $OPENFILE -f 1286739555 $DIR/d33/f33 || true\n+        $RUNAS $OPENFILE -f 21354413143 $DIR/d33/f33 || true\n }\n run_test 33b \"test open file with malformed flags (No panic)\"",
      "accounts_in_message": [],
      "_revision_number": 1
    },
    {
      "id": "12638dc78c2180422814e6c90a57835971745ffb",
      "author": {
        "_account_id": 117,
        "name": "Andreas Dilger",
        "email": "adilger@thelustrecollective.com",
        "username": "adilger"
      },
      "date": "2012-08-29 16:15:51.000000000",
      "message": "Patch Set 1:\n\nShadow,\nthe problem I see isn't with tools like lfs that are packaged with Lustre, or software that is packaged and versioned at all. Instead, the problem iwill be with user applications that are statically linked with liblustreapi.a and are not under any kind of version control.\n\nIt would be possible to add in compatibility code for this, by checking for both the current value and the new value (the value of O_LOV_DELAY_CREATE should be defined with both bits set), so that older binaries will continue to work as long as possible, but newer binaries will be compiled to use both values for some time .  Since newer kernels will mask off the old flag (apparently without any harm) but allow the new value, it should be safe for applications to send both. \n\nFor older releases of Lustre, they could begin to check for either value in the kernel, and send both values from userspace. I don't think there is any way to directly detect from userspace if the kernel is masking this open flag. \n\nIt would also be a good idea to start building a dynamic linked version of liblustreapi.so so that it is possible to fix these sorts of problems without having to recompile the applications. \n\nI'm of course glad that there isn't a protocol issue, since that avoids a lot of further complexity.",
      "accounts_in_message": [],
      "_revision_number": 1
    },
    {
      "id": "eb191f436c0085d55fb64e34a35da96e548de20a",
      "author": {
        "_account_id": 117,
        "name": "Andreas Dilger",
        "email": "adilger@thelustrecollective.com",
        "username": "adilger"
      },
      "date": "2012-08-29 17:01:04.000000000",
      "message": "Patch Set 1:\n\nAs for the option to use an existing flag, what I was actually thinking of was O_ACCMODE and FMODE_WRITE_IOCTL, which is currently used for floppy.c to open the device only for ioctl() of a floppy drive that has no disk inserted.\n\nIt would be desirable to use an existing flag instead of creating a new one, since we may otherwise find ourselves in this situation again in the future, without an easy workaround with no apparent side effects as today. \n\nOne potential concern is that I'm not sure whether it is possible to convert a file opened with O_ACCMODE to having a different open mode afterward or not.  Unlike using some new value for O_LOV_DELAY_CREATE, using O_ACCMODE would affect the core read/write behavior of the file.",
      "accounts_in_message": [],
      "_revision_number": 1
    },
    {
      "id": "e4f405fc32613c5bfb90824b99d17c95f50fc2ef",
      "author": {
        "_account_id": 242,
        "name": "Liu Xuezhao",
        "email": "xuezhao.liu@emc.com",
        "username": "XuezhaoLiu",
        "inactive": true
      },
      "date": "2012-08-30 10:01:53.000000000",
      "message": "Patch Set 1:\n\nThank you all for the comments.\n\nGot to know Andreas' concern about the compatible issue for previously statically linked binary. I think we can temporarily define O_LOV_DELAY_CREATE as a combined bit for the compatible issue. I will update this patch(build .so also for liblustreapi.so.)\n\nHi Iurii Golovach,\n\nI am sorry I didn't understand why sanity.sh's test_33b needs change. \nI tested that the testing of \"$RUNAS $OPENFILE -f 1286739555 $DIR/d33/f33\" can fail as expected (-ENOENT) and pass test_33b. Changing open flag as \"21354413143\" also can fail as expected but it was failed at openfile.c itself (\"No such flag\"). \n\nThanks.",
      "accounts_in_message": [],
      "_revision_number": 1
    },
    {
      "id": "70d3998fbf53591e738239185e51aae238c9ae40",
      "author": {
        "_account_id": 242,
        "name": "Liu Xuezhao",
        "email": "xuezhao.liu@emc.com",
        "username": "XuezhaoLiu",
        "inactive": true
      },
      "date": "2012-08-30 10:07:45.000000000",
      "message": "Patch Set 1:\n\nFor \"file opened with O_ACCMODE\" (with O_ACCMODE and FMODE_WRITE_IOCTL). I did not find a good method to retrieve original's open flag. So I did not change like that. \nWe may open another ticket for it latter if it could work.\n\nI agree that it will be better if we can use an existing flag for it.",
      "accounts_in_message": [],
      "_revision_number": 1
    },
    {
